00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:21.500
"Well, Professor Jentleson,"
one earnest young student said,

00:10:21.500 --> 00:10:23.580
"I think the Cold War will end" --

00:10:23.580 --> 00:10:25.540
this is the early 1980s
-- "and end peacefully."

00:10:25.540 --> 00:10:28.440
And from another bright-eyed
one I got, "Apartheid will end

00:10:28.440 --> 00:10:30.660
in South Africa, and South
Africa will transition

00:10:30.660 --> 00:10:32.190
to a black-majority democracy."

00:10:32.190 --> 00:10:35.050
My responses at the time
were along the lines of,

00:10:35.050 --> 00:10:36.910
"It's nice to be young, naive,

00:10:36.910 --> 00:10:41.000
and California dreaming,
but let's be realistic."

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:44.190
The Cold War did end, and
without a nuclear or other U.S.

00:10:44.190 --> 00:10:45.490
/Soviet war.

00:10:45.490 --> 00:10:49.110 position:56%
Apartheid did end, and the political
transition was impressively civil.

00:10:49.110 --> 00:10:50.650
While many factors came into play,

00:10:50.650 --> 00:10:54.170
the extraordinary statesmanship
provided by Mikhail Gorbachev

00:10:54.170 --> 00:10:56.620
and Nelson Mandela
were the crucial ones.

00:10:56.620 --> 00:10:59.930
So in one of those gratifying
examples of the two-way street

00:10:59.930 --> 00:11:04.460 position:56%
of professors teaching and also
learning from students, and teaching

00:11:04.460 --> 00:11:07.180
and research cross-fertilizing,
I got thinking

00:11:07.180 --> 00:11:08.600
about two other questions.

00:11:08.600 --> 00:11:13.110
Who else in the 20th century
was a profile in statesmanship,

00:11:13.110 --> 00:11:15.460
shaping major breakthroughs
for peace?

00:11:15.460 --> 00:11:17.960
The leaders I include in the
book were not totally successful.

00:11:17.960 --> 00:11:20.280
Gorbachev and Mandela
were not, either.

00:11:20.280 --> 00:11:22.820
But they were transformational,
making breakthroughs on issues

00:11:22.820 --> 00:11:25.840
that have been marked by deep
tensions and intense conflict,

00:11:25.840 --> 00:11:29.520
which made possible, although did
not guarantee further progress.

00:11:29.520 --> 00:11:32.160
And secondly, what can we learn

00:11:32.160 --> 00:11:37.000
from 20th century transformational
statesmanship for the 21st century?

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:41.530
A while back, in the late 1980s,
early 1990s, it sure seemed

00:11:41.530 --> 00:11:43.980
like the world was going
in a good direction.

00:11:43.980 --> 00:11:47.190
The Cold War ended peacefully,
dictatorships were falling

00:11:47.190 --> 00:11:50.540
to democracies, globalization
was spreading the wealth,

00:11:50.540 --> 00:11:54.040
history was said to be over,
world affairs becoming so harmonic

00:11:54.040 --> 00:11:56.320
as to be downright boring.

00:11:56.320 --> 00:11:57.620
As Jason said in our interview,

00:11:57.620 --> 00:11:59.170
things have not exactly
worked out that way.

00:11:59.170 --> 00:12:01.740
The end of the Cold War has
not meant the end of war.

00:12:01.740 --> 00:12:05.810
That democratic wave has
broken up on some rocky shores.

00:12:05.810 --> 00:12:08.610
Globalization has had
losers as well as winners,

00:12:08.610 --> 00:12:10.580
downsides as well as upsides.

00:12:10.580 --> 00:12:12.370
History has come roaring back

00:12:12.370 --> 00:12:14.950
with ancient hatreds
fueled by modern venoms.

00:12:14.950 --> 00:12:16.250
Climate change is speeding up.

00:12:16.250 --> 00:12:18.520
Global health pandemics
are spreading.

00:12:18.520 --> 00:12:21.920 position:56%
Cyberwar and other technology-driven
emerging areas in need of rules

00:12:21.920 --> 00:12:23.940
of the game aren't getting them.

00:12:23.940 --> 00:12:26.710 position:56%
Indeed, it is a lot easier to name
a global problem that's been growing

00:12:26.710 --> 00:12:29.030
worse than one in which
progress has been made.

00:12:29.030 --> 00:12:34.120
So as I thought about these
two questions and started

00:12:34.120 --> 00:12:36.630
to develop my thinking on it,
they really bring you back to one

00:12:36.630 --> 00:12:39.080
of those questions that's been
debated forever, you know,

00:12:39.080 --> 00:12:42.340
does history make statesmen
or do statesmen make history?

00:12:42.340 --> 00:12:47.140
You know, at one end of the
debate is Thomas Carlyle's heroic

00:12:47.140 --> 00:12:49.500
conception of history that, quote,

00:12:49.500 --> 00:12:52.280
"The history of what man has
accomplished in this world is

00:12:52.280 --> 00:12:55.510
at bottom the history of the
great men who have worked here.

00:12:55.510 --> 00:12:57.420
All thing that we see
standing accomplished

00:12:57.420 --> 00:13:00.920
in the world are properly
the outer material result --

00:13:00.920 --> 00:13:04.350
the practical realization
embodiment of thoughts that dwelt

00:13:04.350 --> 00:13:07.180
in the great men sent
into the world."

00:13:07.180 --> 00:13:09.980
The other end of the
debate is Herbert Spencer

00:13:09.980 --> 00:13:13.120
who derided the universal
love of personalities,

00:13:13.120 --> 00:13:17.580 position:56%
going back well before "People"
magazine and TMZ.com to when, quote,

00:13:17.580 --> 00:13:21.010
"Round the campfire assembled
savages telling the events

00:13:21.010 --> 00:13:25.050 position:56%
of the day's chase, and he among
them who has done some feat of skill

00:13:25.050 --> 00:13:27.500
or agility is duly lauded."

00:13:27.500 --> 00:13:29.330
The truth lies in between.

00:13:29.330 --> 00:13:32.900 position:56%
Carlyle is too much the romanticist,
overstating the roles of individuals

00:13:32.900 --> 00:13:36.320
and undervaluing conducive
conditions creating opportunities

00:13:36.320 --> 00:13:37.720
for leadership.

00:13:37.720 --> 00:13:41.970 position:56%
Spencer is too much the sociologist,
overstating societal processes

00:13:41.970 --> 00:13:45.790
and contexts, and undervaluing
what, as many people find,

00:13:45.790 --> 00:13:50.910
and Isaiah Berlin said, "At
crucial moments at turning points,

00:13:50.910 --> 00:13:52.480
individuals and their decisions

00:13:52.480 --> 00:13:55.950
and acts can determine
the course of history."

00:13:55.950 --> 00:13:58.930
My perspective, based on experience
in the foreign policy world as well

00:13:58.930 --> 00:14:02.260
as an international relations
professor, puts me in this history

00:14:02.260 --> 00:14:04.700
of great leaders' middle ground.

00:14:04.700 --> 00:14:07.410
The academic literature digs deeper
than just the latest who's up

00:14:07.410 --> 00:14:10.840
and who's down, but too often
stays at a level of abstraction

00:14:10.840 --> 00:14:13.970
that glosses over the
impact that leaders do have.

00:14:13.970 --> 00:14:16.870 position:56%
The talk here inside the Beltway and
among journalists can get too caught

00:14:16.870 --> 00:14:19.560
up in personalities,
but often does focus

00:14:19.560 --> 00:14:23.090
in on critical decision
making and strategizing.

00:14:23.090 --> 00:14:25.330
The analytic balance is in
recognizing that history

00:14:25.330 --> 00:14:28.180
and broad social forces
create constraints as well

00:14:28.180 --> 00:14:32.580
as conducive conditions, shaping
the range of available choices.

00:14:32.580 --> 00:14:35.730
But they don't determine
what choices get made.

00:14:35.730 --> 00:14:37.510
No individual is so
extraordinary that he

00:14:37.510 --> 00:14:40.820
or she would have transformational
impact, irrespective of the context

00:14:40.820 --> 00:14:42.890
in which he or she
ends up operating.

00:14:42.890 --> 00:14:46.720
But it's also not a given that just
anyone could have pulled off the

00:14:46.720 --> 00:14:49.920
statesmanship that the
particular leader did.

00:14:49.920 --> 00:14:52.720
It's man, woman, and
moment, fit, and timing.

00:14:52.720 --> 00:14:55.240
And so as I've thought
about this in the book,

00:14:55.240 --> 00:14:59.670 position:56%
I think of it as a framework of what
I call the three Cs, the constraints

00:14:59.670 --> 00:15:05.070
that limit the choices that leaders
have, the conducive conditions

00:15:05.070 --> 00:15:07.810
that help make it possible
to make certain choices,

00:15:07.810 --> 00:15:10.890
but ultimately really
about choices being made.

00:15:10.890 --> 00:15:17.130
The -- Fred Greenstein, who
was a noted political scientist

00:15:17.130 --> 00:15:20.960
at Princeton, in his worked talked
in more formal social science terms

00:15:20.960 --> 00:15:25.340
about actor indispensability,
that the leader

00:15:25.340 --> 00:15:28.670
in question responds significantly
differently than another leader

00:15:28.670 --> 00:15:31.010
in the same situation would have.

00:15:31.010 --> 00:15:33.690
And Greenstein says this is
especially true in situations

00:15:33.690 --> 00:15:37.220
like transformational statesmanship
when, as he puts it, quote,

00:15:37.220 --> 00:15:40.580
"The more demanding the political
act, the greater the likelihood

00:15:40.580 --> 00:15:41.880
that it will be influenced

00:15:41.880 --> 00:15:44.100
by personal characteristics
of the actor."

00:15:44.100 --> 00:15:46.980
So yes, there are systemic
forces at work at many levels,

00:15:46.980 --> 00:15:49.230
but choices that are made.

00:15:49.230 --> 00:15:54.790
Another way of thinking about this
is in baseball moneyball terms,

00:15:54.790 --> 00:15:57.360
right, the statistic of
wins-against-replacement,

00:15:57.360 --> 00:16:01.810 position:56%
which calculates how much one
player contributes to team victories

00:16:01.810 --> 00:16:03.700
over alternative ones
at the same position.

00:16:03.700 --> 00:16:08.170
And one gets into very
complicated sabermetrics on this.

00:16:08.170 --> 00:16:12.010
So while there is no neat
diplo-ball statesmanship

00:16:12.010 --> 00:16:16.010
against replacement leader
sabermetric, or SARL,

00:16:16.010 --> 00:16:18.480
evidence can be marshalled to make
the same point, who the player

00:16:18.480 --> 00:16:20.460
or statesman is makes a big
difference, and frankly,

00:16:20.460 --> 00:16:23.610
it allows me to connect my
passion for baseball and my work

00:16:23.610 --> 00:16:26.460
in foreign policy, which
at least two people

00:16:26.460 --> 00:16:28.260
in the audience will
know is something I try

00:16:28.260 --> 00:16:30.210
to do as often as possible.

00:16:30.210 --> 00:16:34.010
So we can think about this in
the broader sense of leadership

00:16:34.010 --> 00:16:36.570
as genus leadership,
species statesmanship.

00:16:36.570 --> 00:16:41.200
And there is a huge
literature on this.

00:16:41.200 --> 00:16:43.850
James MacGregor Burns, very
distinguished scholar on this,

00:16:43.850 --> 00:16:46.110
called leadership, "One
of the most observed

00:16:46.110 --> 00:16:47.760
and least understood
phenomena on earth."

00:16:47.760 --> 00:16:51.890 position:56%
Noted author and public intellectual
Walter Isaacson calls it an

00:16:51.890 --> 00:16:53.190
"elusive quality."

00:16:53.190 --> 00:16:56.580
That's not for a lack of trying.

00:16:56.580 --> 00:16:57.880
Books abound.

00:16:57.880 --> 00:17:00.390 position:56%
Some are about political leadership,
some about business leadership,

00:17:00.390 --> 00:17:03.060
some philosophical, some how-to.

00:17:03.060 --> 00:17:07.350
And an Amazon search
brought up 173,164 books

00:17:07.350 --> 00:17:12.930
for keyword leadership, 79,455
for political leadership.

00:17:12.930 --> 00:17:14.230
Nor are there a shortage

00:17:14.230 --> 00:17:15.780
of university-based
leadership programs.

00:17:15.780 --> 00:17:18.260
Harvard has its Advanced
Leadership Institute.

00:17:18.260 --> 00:17:20.190
At Duke we have our
Hard Leadership program.

00:17:20.190 --> 00:17:22.930
The University of Virginia has
the Batten School of Leadership

00:17:22.930 --> 00:17:24.480
and Public Policy, and many others.

00:17:24.480 --> 00:17:28.460 position:56%
In the corporate world an
estimated $14 billion has been spent

00:17:28.460 --> 00:17:29.760
over the past two decades

00:17:29.760 --> 00:17:33.110
on leadership development,
twice as much as before.

00:17:33.110 --> 00:17:37.740
Yet 75% of respondents deem
their programs ineffective.

00:17:37.740 --> 00:17:39.920
Indeed, as we know in many context,

00:17:39.920 --> 00:17:43.050
people talk about leadership all
the time, but with the same mantra

00:17:43.050 --> 00:17:46.470
of we need leadership,
and how do you get it?

00:17:46.470 --> 00:17:49.300
And there's a sense of both
fascination and frustration.

00:17:49.300 --> 00:17:53.660
Fascination in how time and again
explanations of success and failure

00:17:53.660 --> 00:17:56.680
in such a range of
professions and pursuits hone

00:17:56.680 --> 00:17:58.790
in on leadership as a key factor.

00:17:58.790 --> 00:18:02.830
Frustration in how difficult it is
to find the elements of leadership

00:18:02.830 --> 00:18:07.040
with any degree of consistency,
let alone teach and cultivate them.

00:18:07.040 --> 00:18:10.250
My intent in this book is to tap
the fascination and at least try

00:18:10.250 --> 00:18:12.750
to reduce the frustration.

00:18:12.750 --> 00:18:16.980
So in working with this literature
on leadership broadly defined,

00:18:16.980 --> 00:18:22.760
I've derived and I use in the book
a four-part analytic framework

00:18:22.760 --> 00:18:26.870
which has the who, why,
how, what questions.

00:18:26.870 --> 00:18:29.690
Who were these leaders
as individuals?

00:18:29.690 --> 00:18:32.340
Why did the make the
crucial choices they did?

00:18:32.340 --> 00:18:34.420
How did they pursue their goals?

00:18:34.420 --> 00:18:36.090
And what was and wasn't achieved?

00:18:36.090 --> 00:18:38.290
Let me talk a little bit about
that framework before getting

00:18:38.290 --> 00:18:43.120
into the profiles of who
I focus on in the book.

00:18:43.120 --> 00:18:44.730
Who were these leaders
as individuals?

00:18:44.730 --> 00:18:47.470
Here we kind of want to get to
know them a little bit as people

00:18:47.470 --> 00:18:49.360
without putting them on
the couch and doing sort

00:18:49.360 --> 00:18:52.750
of a deterministic,
psychoanalytic analysis.

00:18:52.750 --> 00:18:55.730
"A man's rootage [sic]," as
Woodrow Wilson once said,

00:18:55.730 --> 00:18:58.050
"means more than his leafage."

00:18:58.050 --> 00:19:00.980
But it's not about
being a born leader.

00:19:00.980 --> 00:19:03.080
Rarely is there a statesmanship
equivalent

00:19:03.080 --> 00:19:05.870
of Mozart the five-year-old
prodigy or LeBron James

00:19:05.870 --> 00:19:10.530 position:56%
with NBA superstar skills coming out
of high school, or a perfect person,

00:19:10.530 --> 00:19:15.480
Nelson Mandela in his
own personal life was --

00:19:15.480 --> 00:19:18.830
issues with his own family,
with is wives and his children.

00:19:18.830 --> 00:19:20.750
There are, though, some
certain personal qualities

00:19:20.750 --> 00:19:25.540
that do bear heavily
on leadership capacity.

00:19:25.540 --> 00:19:31.610
One is what is called by some
in the literature moral capital,

00:19:31.610 --> 00:19:33.710
which is a little different
than political capital.

00:19:33.710 --> 00:19:37.570
It's a justness of what you stand
for, and of you as the leader

00:19:37.570 --> 00:19:40.120
of that cause and for that purpose.

00:19:40.120 --> 00:19:42.300
And so legitimacy is
perceived by those

00:19:42.300 --> 00:19:44.900
to whom you would provide
the leadership.

00:19:44.900 --> 00:19:48.010
One of the factors that goes
into this is personal courage,

00:19:48.010 --> 00:19:50.910
the sacrifices endured,
the hardships suffered,

00:19:50.910 --> 00:19:56.240
in many cases prison
sentences, the willingness

00:19:56.240 --> 00:19:58.370
to take courageous stands.

00:19:58.370 --> 00:20:02.280
As two scholars on leadership
at Harvard put it, they said,

00:20:02.280 --> 00:20:04.480
