00:22:16.730 --> 00:22:18.610
the values which the
present is violating

00:22:18.610 --> 00:22:22.320
and the alternative future
will affirm; the symbolic,

00:22:22.320 --> 00:22:25.530
tapping deeply-rooted
cultural beliefs and mores,

00:22:25.530 --> 00:22:28.500
and avoiding taboos that infuse
judgments of the legitimacy

00:22:28.500 --> 00:22:31.490 position:56%
of the vision; and a cognitive
element, the key substantive points,

00:22:31.490 --> 00:22:34.340
and the critique, and
the alternative.

00:22:34.340 --> 00:22:36.700
How is really a question
of politics and strategy,

00:22:36.700 --> 00:22:38.820
what Joe Nye in his
work on this quotes,

00:22:38.820 --> 00:22:41.730
"The means to achieve the
ends in one's vision."

00:22:41.730 --> 00:22:44.420
Robert Rotberg, who's
written a lot on leaders

00:22:44.420 --> 00:22:46.660
in the developing world
says leaders --

00:22:46.660 --> 00:22:49.380
transformational leaders
can't just be visionaries.

00:22:49.380 --> 00:22:51.420
They have to be navigators.

00:22:51.420 --> 00:22:54.580
Nan Keohane, President of Duke for
many years and a political theorist

00:22:54.580 --> 00:23:00.770
in her own right, talks about not
just making decisions, but devising

00:23:00.770 --> 00:23:04.360 position:56%
and implementing strategies with
the right combination of incentives.

00:23:04.360 --> 00:23:08.300
Heifetz and Lipsky at Harvard talk
about controlling the temperature,

00:23:08.300 --> 00:23:09.600
keeping the opposition close.

00:23:09.600 --> 00:23:11.820
And in deed, in the
stories that I tell,

00:23:11.820 --> 00:23:14.630
when these have been violated it
also points to ways in which some

00:23:14.630 --> 00:23:17.470
of these leaders have not
achieved the full transformations

00:23:17.470 --> 00:23:18.770
that they've wanted.

00:23:18.770 --> 00:23:23.620
The what did and what didn't they
achieve, to quote Machiavelli,

00:23:23.620 --> 00:23:26.320
"There is nothing more difficult
to carry out, nor more doubtful

00:23:26.320 --> 00:23:28.870
of success, nor more
dangerous to handle

00:23:28.870 --> 00:23:31.370
than to initiate a
new order of things.

00:23:31.370 --> 00:23:33.800
And here I take the
transformational balance sheet,

00:23:33.800 --> 00:23:36.850
and sort of net assessing in
each case what was lessons

00:23:36.850 --> 00:23:39.030
and what was and wasn't achieved.

00:23:39.030 --> 00:23:43.340
Recall that Isaiah Berlin quote in
which he talked about individuals

00:23:43.340 --> 00:23:48.780
that can determine the course of
history, not necessarily they do,

00:23:48.780 --> 00:23:50.980
which comes back to the
three Cs, constraints,

00:23:50.980 --> 00:23:53.030
conducive conditions, and choices.

00:23:53.030 --> 00:23:55.070
Breakthroughs also have backlashes.

00:23:55.070 --> 00:23:57.690
And here it's important to
draw the lessons, as I said,

00:23:57.690 --> 00:24:00.000
between what was achieved
and what wasn't.

00:24:00.000 --> 00:24:02.260 position:56%
So that's the [inaudible] framework.

00:24:02.260 --> 00:24:06.920
Quickly sort of the criteria
for choosing the cases in terms

00:24:06.920 --> 00:24:10.920
of the research design, I
focus on 20th century cases,

00:24:10.920 --> 00:24:12.380
which is really more
my own expertise

00:24:12.380 --> 00:24:15.820
than prior historical periods in
a sense of what's most pertinent

00:24:15.820 --> 00:24:19.210
for 21st century lesson drawing.

00:24:19.210 --> 00:24:21.740
Transformational statesmanship
and the work of people

00:24:21.740 --> 00:24:23.110
like Janet Berger Burns
[assumed spelling]

00:24:23.110 --> 00:24:26.440
and Joe Nye is distinguished
from transactional diplomacy.

00:24:26.440 --> 00:24:29.620
Transformational being efforts
to make major breakthroughs

00:24:29.620 --> 00:24:33.420
in global peace and security as
distinct from diplomacy geared

00:24:33.420 --> 00:24:36.650
to managing and resolving issues
in the normal course of events,

00:24:36.650 --> 00:24:40.890
which is not to belittle importance
of transactional diplomacy.

00:24:40.890 --> 00:24:46.240
It's very important on a day-to-day
basis, but it's just not my focus

00:24:46.240 --> 00:24:50.390
in this particular book, trying
to look at those breakpoints.

00:24:50.390 --> 00:24:54.010
Third is the impact had, not
so much the position held.

00:24:54.010 --> 00:24:56.560
Typically when we think of
statesmanship we turn to presidents

00:24:56.560 --> 00:25:00.260 position:56%
and prime ministers, secretaries of
state, ministers of foreign affairs,

00:25:00.260 --> 00:25:02.580
and other leaders of nation-states.

00:25:02.580 --> 00:25:05.030
While I emphasize national
leaders, I'm also inclusive

00:25:05.030 --> 00:25:07.850
of transformational leaders
for international institutions,

00:25:07.850 --> 00:25:11.260
from social movements and
NGOs who did for peace

00:25:11.260 --> 00:25:15.910
and justice what governments
were unable or unwilling to do.

00:25:15.910 --> 00:25:18.710 position:56%
This is the sense of
statesmanship less strictly in terms

00:25:18.710 --> 00:25:24.370 position:56%
of the position held than the impact
had on global peace and security.

00:25:24.370 --> 00:25:27.580
Twentieth century breakthroughs,
21st century lessons based

00:25:27.580 --> 00:25:30.290
on these profiles, not
so much to point at this

00:25:30.290 --> 00:25:33.050
or that leader floating
around the 21st century world.

00:25:33.050 --> 00:25:35.420
Indeed, if someone tried
to do that with many

00:25:35.420 --> 00:25:38.940
of the 20th century profiles,
we would miss quite a few.

00:25:38.940 --> 00:25:41.450
But drawing lessons
for different areas,

00:25:41.450 --> 00:25:44.910
for overcoming the difficulties,
maximizing the possibilities,

00:25:44.910 --> 00:25:47.010
and achieving what is necessary.

00:25:47.010 --> 00:25:49.840
And when I think about
global peace and security,

00:25:49.840 --> 00:25:52.670
it's a rather large subject.

00:25:52.670 --> 00:25:56.640 position:56%
To get a handle on it, I break it
