00:28:17.860 --> 00:28:23.480
The opening to China was
really Kissinger's best.

00:28:23.480 --> 00:28:25.530
It entailed realpolitik
strategizing,

00:28:25.530 --> 00:28:27.400
or great power politics.

00:28:27.400 --> 00:28:29.150
It required the face-to-face
diplomacy

00:28:29.150 --> 00:28:31.340
that his persona so well suited.

00:28:31.340 --> 00:28:34.380
It worked through back channels and
secret meetings as was his want.

00:28:34.380 --> 00:28:36.930
It maneuvered the superpower
triangle in ways

00:28:36.930 --> 00:28:39.660
that reinforced Soviet
incentives for detente.

00:28:39.660 --> 00:28:41.470
Zhou Enlai was very
much the equal partner.

00:28:41.470 --> 00:28:44.630
He was that extraordinary mix
of committed revolutionary,

00:28:44.630 --> 00:28:47.400
pragmatic diplomat, and what
some would call the last mandarin

00:28:47.400 --> 00:28:49.180
bureaucrat in the Confucian
tradition.

00:28:49.180 --> 00:28:52.160
Had Las Vegas bookies known

00:28:52.160 --> 00:28:55.340
about the secret Kissinger-Zhou
meetings representing two countries

00:28:55.340 --> 00:28:57.740
that have been enemies
for 20-plus years,

00:28:57.740 --> 00:29:00.460
that regularly demonized one
another politically and culturally,

00:29:00.460 --> 00:29:04.440
that had burning issues like U.S.
support for Taiwan and Chinese aid

00:29:04.440 --> 00:29:07.250
to North Vietnam, no doubt the
betting odds would have been

00:29:07.250 --> 00:29:08.870
on breakdown.

00:29:08.870 --> 00:29:12.240
One of the keys was making
the transactional serve

00:29:12.240 --> 00:29:13.770
the transformational.

00:29:13.770 --> 00:29:16.090
Compromising on issues
like Taiwan and Vietnam,

00:29:16.090 --> 00:29:19.920
conscious of the larger strategic
stakes, recognizing that,

00:29:19.920 --> 00:29:22.500 position:56%
as Zhou put it, "Only the settlement

00:29:22.500 --> 00:29:24.610
of fundamental questions
first can lead

00:29:24.610 --> 00:29:26.590
to the settlement of
other questions."

00:29:26.590 --> 00:29:29.020
And I think that's a very
significant statement that relates

00:29:29.020 --> 00:29:31.820
to any number of issues one
can think about today, U.S.

00:29:31.820 --> 00:29:33.120
/Russia, U.S.

00:29:33.120 --> 00:29:34.420
/China, perhaps U.S.

00:29:34.420 --> 00:29:36.750
/Iran, only the settlement of
fundamental questions that can lead

00:29:36.750 --> 00:29:39.580
to the settlement of
other questions.

00:29:39.580 --> 00:29:43.370
It's true there are other
players in this, President Nixon

00:29:43.370 --> 00:29:45.740
and Chairman Mao were of
course also major players,

00:29:45.740 --> 00:29:47.430
and they did get the opera.

00:29:47.430 --> 00:29:51.100
But Kissinger and Zhou were
the statecraft strategists.

00:29:52.770 --> 00:29:55.910
Gorbachev made the key decision
to bring the Cold War to an end.

00:29:55.910 --> 00:29:57.920
And while he gets the
bulk of the credit,

00:29:57.920 --> 00:30:00.460
some also goes to Ronald Reagan.

00:30:00.460 --> 00:30:03.170
It wasn't as essentially equal
a role as Kissinger and Zhou,

00:30:03.170 --> 00:30:05.890
so I do bring Reagan
into the analysis more

00:30:05.890 --> 00:30:07.770
than some, less than others.

00:30:07.770 --> 00:30:10.650
I focus the profile
principally on Gorbachev.

00:30:10.650 --> 00:30:14.110
As bad as things were for the
Soviet Union, the Afghanistan War,

00:30:14.110 --> 00:30:19.110
the economy, restiveness all over
Eastern Europe, it wasn't a given

00:30:19.110 --> 00:30:21.560
that another Soviet leader
would have made the decisions

00:30:21.560 --> 00:30:25.120
that Gorbachev did, thus
the statesmanship moneyball.

00:30:25.120 --> 00:30:28.780
While Gorbachev acknowledges
his own leadership failures,

00:30:28.780 --> 00:30:32.390
as he says in his memoirs, quote,
"Looking back, on can see blemishes

00:30:32.390 --> 00:30:35.570
and mistakes that could have
been avoided," and while he ended

00:30:35.570 --> 00:30:39.270 position:56%
up eliminated from the Russian
political scene, his impact endured.

00:30:39.270 --> 00:30:40.570
The Cold War ended.

00:30:40.570 --> 00:30:41.870
It ended peacefully.

00:30:41.870 --> 00:30:44.320
And Vladimir Putin notwithstanding,
today's tensions are nothing

00:30:44.320 --> 00:30:47.180
like the competition between
nuclear arms superpowers

00:30:47.180 --> 00:30:49.870
with global ambitions
and competing ideologies

00:30:49.870 --> 00:30:51.410
that largely define the world scene

00:30:51.410 --> 00:30:52.920
for the second half
of the 20th century.

00:30:52.920 --> 00:30:55.560
So when you hear people
talking about the New Cold War,

00:30:55.560 --> 00:30:57.440
I think what we're
seeing is a major power --

00:30:57.440 --> 00:30:59.710
a classical major power competition

00:30:59.710 --> 00:31:01.500
between the United
States and Russia.

00:31:01.500 --> 00:31:06.350
But we shouldn't forget what
the Cold War was really about.

00:31:06.350 --> 00:31:09.920
And so my argument is that
endured despite the current state

00:31:09.920 --> 00:31:11.920
of relations.

00:31:11.920 --> 00:31:15.460
For a while, of course, it
seemed like the great game

00:31:15.460 --> 00:31:18.210
of major politics might
be a thing of the past.

00:31:18.210 --> 00:31:20.530
Russian and American
leaders were embracing,

00:31:20.530 --> 00:31:22.420
Bill Clinton and Boris Yeltsin.

00:31:22.420 --> 00:31:25.330
Peering into each other's eyes
and getting a sense of his soul,

00:31:25.330 --> 00:31:28.140
George W. Bush after his
first meeting with Putin.

00:31:28.140 --> 00:31:30.680
Declaring a reset to get
relations back on track,

00:31:30.680 --> 00:31:33.860
Barrack Obama and Dmitry Medvedev.

00:31:33.860 --> 00:31:36.390
The interweaving of China into
the global economy was supposed

00:31:36.390 --> 00:31:37.690
to temper its rise.

00:31:37.690 --> 00:31:40.520
The United States claimed to be
playing its leadership role in ways

00:31:40.520 --> 00:31:43.550
that were in the interest of the
overall international community.

00:31:43.550 --> 00:31:45.040
But again, it hasn't
worked out that way.

00:31:45.040 --> 00:31:48.220 position:56%
Russia has been more aggressive
than at any time since the Cold War;

00:31:48.220 --> 00:31:49.950
China has been flexing
its muscles in Asia;

00:31:49.950 --> 00:31:53.280
and the Bush Administration went
to war in Iraq over the opposition

00:31:53.280 --> 00:31:55.440
of much of the world;
the expectation

00:31:55.440 --> 00:31:57.470
that greeted Barrack Obama
that all will be fine

00:31:57.470 --> 00:32:00.510
with a more multilateralist
American President was not met

00:32:00.510 --> 00:32:04.250
in any enduring way over the
course of his presidency.

00:32:04.250 --> 00:32:07.670
And what comes next
in the United States?

00:32:07.670 --> 00:32:09.420
Separate conversation [chuckle].

00:32:09.420 --> 00:32:11.250
But as we try to get U.S.

00:32:11.250 --> 00:32:13.890 position:56%
/Russia/China relations on a better
track, there are a number of lessons

00:32:13.890 --> 00:32:16.810
that I try to draw out from
the Kissinger/Zhou relationship

00:32:16.810 --> 00:32:19.800
and the Gorbachev breakthrough.

00:32:19.800 --> 00:32:21.830 position:56%
Building international institutions,
when I was first thinking

00:32:21.830 --> 00:32:27.150 position:56%
about the book I really had Wilson
very much in mind for the main focus

00:32:27.150 --> 00:32:29.370
of international institutions,
you know, making the world safe

00:32:29.370 --> 00:32:32.300
for democracy, international
cooperation through new League

00:32:32.300 --> 00:32:35.190
of Nations, Wilsonianism as
an enduring school of thought.

00:32:35.190 --> 00:32:38.700 position:56%
But the more I dug into the reading,
much of which I actually did

00:32:38.700 --> 00:32:42.860
at the Wilson Center on this
part, in research about Wilson,

00:32:42.860 --> 00:32:46.350 position:56%
the more the limits of his
transformationalism became apparent.

00:32:46.350 --> 00:32:48.910
The standard view that Americans
were just bent on retreating

00:32:48.910 --> 00:32:52.550
into isolationism after the Great
War is actually much too knee-jerk.

00:32:52.550 --> 00:32:54.510
When you look at actually
the politics of the moment,

00:32:54.510 --> 00:32:56.840
Wilson could have gotten
the Versailles Treaty

00:32:56.840 --> 00:32:58.620 position:56%
and U.S. League membership ratified,

00:32:58.620 --> 00:33:02.050
but he hugely mismanaged
the domestic politics.

00:33:02.050 --> 00:33:03.350
And for all his high-mindedness,

00:33:03.350 --> 00:33:06.290
the design of the League
was fundamentally flawed.

00:33:06.290 --> 00:33:09.040
So it's the limits of Wilson's
transformational statesmanship

00:33:09.040 --> 00:33:13.380
that's instructive and that I use
as sort of an initial mini-profile.

00:33:13.380 --> 00:33:15.310
FDR as the principle architect

00:33:15.310 --> 00:33:17.840
of the U.N. succeeded
where Wilson didn't.

00:33:17.840 --> 00:33:21.180
While designing an international
institution is its own active

00:33:21.180 --> 00:33:24.770
statesmanship, his untimely
death meant that he never got

00:33:24.770 --> 00:33:27.070
to play a direct role in
bringing it to fruition.

00:33:27.070 --> 00:33:30.440
Had he lived, his imprint on the
U.N. may have been even greater.

00:33:30.440 --> 00:33:33.760
Another we'll-never-know
is whether FDR's musings

00:33:33.760 --> 00:33:36.460
about resigning the presidency
and taking up the leadership

00:33:36.460 --> 00:33:38.020 position:56%
of the U.N. would have come to pass.

00:33:38.020 --> 00:33:42.920
As things turned out, the first
U.N. Secretary General, Trygve Lie,

00:33:42.920 --> 00:33:45.370
had such a difficult time in the
position that he left, calling it,

00:33:45.370 --> 00:33:47.410
quote, "The most impossible
job in the world."

00:33:47.410 --> 00:33:51.520
Lie's successor Dag Hammarskjold
would prove differently.

00:33:51.520 --> 00:33:56.610
And he more than any other
leader showed how impactful an

00:33:56.610 --> 00:34:00.210
international institution
the United Nations could be.

00:34:00.210 --> 00:34:04.280
He made the position a genuine
leadership one, a secular pope,

00:34:04.280 --> 00:34:05.910
as he and others called it,

00:34:05.910 --> 00:34:07.510
and showed what the
U.N. could contribute

00:34:07.510 --> 00:34:10.000
to building global
peace and security.

00:34:10.000 --> 00:34:11.470
This comes through
in his overall effort

00:34:11.470 --> 00:34:13.170
to strengthen the U.N.
institutionally,

00:34:13.170 --> 00:34:16.350
guided by a conception of the
international public servant,

00:34:16.350 --> 00:34:18.770
and especially in his handling
of three crises that I focus

00:34:18.770 --> 00:34:23.090
on in the book, American/Korean War
POWs held by the People's Republic

00:34:23.090 --> 00:34:28.640
of China in 1954, the
1956 Suez Crisis spurred

00:34:28.640 --> 00:34:30.650
by the British/French/Israel
invasion of Egypt,

00:34:30.650 --> 00:34:33.690
and the 1960-61 Congo Crisis.

00:34:33.690 --> 00:34:37.650
At a time in which the world
needs a more effective U.N. --

00:34:37.650 --> 00:34:39.490
other international
institutions as well,

00:34:39.490 --> 00:34:42.310 position:56%
but the U.N. having the most bearing
on global peace and security --

00:34:42.310 --> 00:34:46.230
there is much to be learned
from someone who was eulogized

00:34:46.230 --> 00:34:49.080
by U.S. Ambassador to the U.N.
Adlai Stevenson as, quote,

00:34:49.080 --> 00:34:52.800
"A brilliant mind, a brave
and compassionate spirit.

00:34:52.800 --> 00:34:55.290
I doubt if any living man has
done more to further the search

00:34:55.290 --> 00:34:59.100 position:56%
for a world in which men solve their
problems by peaceful means and not

00:34:59.100 --> 00:35:01.370
by force than this
gallant friend of us all."

00:35:01.370 --> 00:35:04.830
The final part of this chapter lays
out what I call the job description

00:35:04.830 --> 00:35:08.690
for a 21st century
Hammarskjoldian Secretary General.

00:35:08.690 --> 00:35:11.430
While this is not the only element
of making the U.N. more effective,

00:35:11.430 --> 00:35:14.500
and while a more effective U.N.
is not the only international

00:35:14.500 --> 00:35:18.850
institutional reform needed, a
more effective U.N. won't happen

00:35:18.850 --> 00:35:21.410
without a Secretary General
with the statesmanship qualities

00:35:21.410 --> 00:35:22.710
Hammarskjold had.

00:35:22.710 --> 00:35:24.730
And without an effective U.N.,

00:35:24.730 --> 00:35:27.800 position:56%
other international
institutional reforms won't suffice.

00:35:27.800 --> 00:35:31.220
So the way I'm doing this is I'm
